+Metal8Ball
There is a significant undercurrent of racism both within the Republican 
party and within the Republican voter base, that much is a fact, but I 
agree that it's unfair to simply generalize Republicans as racist. 
Republicans are neither outsiders, as implied by "xenophobia", nor a 
"minority people-group", the demonization and scapegoating of which is a 
mark of fascism, however. That's not to minimize it or say that it's not 
bad, but it's not what I'm talking about - if you'll review my previous 
comments, you'll see that I was quite specific in defining my terms.

How on earth is progressivism a supremacist movement? As far as "bogus 
claims, examples and polls", sure, there's some of that: the oft-cited "77 
cents to the dollar" wage gap claim is one example. I also think that the 
effects of raising the minimum wage are far more debatable than either side 
gives the other credit for: Working and middle class individuals spend a 
higher percentage of their income than upper class individuals, meaning 
that the more wealth is concentrated around the working and middle class, 
the more it gets recirculated. However, it's not clear that minimum wage 
laws are an effective way of doing that, as prices may simply scale with 
the lower and middle class's increased purchasing power (and price controls 
are a bad solution with a terrible track record). However, on the whole, I 
have far more faith in progressive economics than I do in Laissez-faire 
economics or supply-side economics in general really, and tend to favor 
stimulus over austerity. Shitty regulation (e.g. the repeal of 
Glass-Steagall, the passing of the Commodity Futures Modernization Act of 
2000, like...the shadow banking system in general) was at the heart of the 
subprime mortgage crisis of 2007, and is a trend that neo-cons, 
libertarians, and corporatist democrats alike will be sure to continue. But 
you know who would definitely oppose that trend? A real progressive. And as 
for austerity measures, they have a pretty garbage track-record whenever 
they're the main component of an economic recovery plan (as they tend to be 
under conservative leadership). Of course, this isn't to say that austerity 
measures are bad per se; spending cuts in one area can be productive when 
used to supplement significant investment in other areas (and of course, 
whether it pays off on balance depends on what you're cutting), and cutting 
needless expenditures is just common sense. That's why progressives (and 
libertarians, who are at least ideologically consistent) would make 
substantial cuts to America's ridiculously bloated defense budget, which at 
$598.49 billion accounted for 53.71% of all discretionary spending in 2015:

https://www.nationalpriorities.org/budget-basics/federal-budget-101/spending/

This is roughly the size of the nine next biggest military budgets in the 
world combined and accounts for 37% of total world military spending (in a 
world made up of almost 200 countries):

https://www.nationalpriorities.org/campaigns/us-military-spending-vs-world/

Establishment politicians and their dupes love to characterize real 
liberals as out-of-control spenders, all while ignoring the massive 
elephant in the room: THEY'RE the ones responsible for our largest 
expenditure BY FAR outside of mandatory government spending; progressives 
and libertarians and the only factions that largely oppose it. The idea 
that this kind of budget is necessary for national defense is literally 
preposterous. Rather, it is the result of our government's cozy relations 
with the military industrial complex and an aggressive foreign policy which 
benefits no country in the long run. A progressive or libertarian would 
want to reign in our impractical and ultimately destructive interventionist 
tendencies and save a fortune as a result. But neither Clinton, nor Trump, 
nor anyone else left on the field save Sanders is going to do any such 
thing. You either vote for a progressive or a libertarian or you get 
shafted on this issue, and considering libertarian ideas on taxes and 
government regulation, I'm not too keen on that second option.

There's also the tremendously pressing threat of climate change. 97% of 
climate scientists agree that not only is global warming real, human beings 
are the main cause. Donald Trump thinks that global warming is mostly a 
hoax, wants to cut the EPA, and referred to green energy as "just an 
expensive feel-good for tree-huggers". Hillary Clinton is an incrementalist 
who will enact small amounts of change too slowly to effectively address 
the catastrophe that's coming. Libertarians, seeming as they've become 
pertinent to the discussion, don't want to regulate polluters and would 
like to get rid of the EPA entirely. It seems to me that ONLY a progressive 
is likely to be an effective leader in addressing climate change.

A progressive is the most likely to fight for campaign finance reform, as 
well. I consider this the single most important issue in politics today, 
because it affects every other issue. It's true that there's a ton of 
bipartisan support for this, but it's mostly at the state level or among 
the electorate. Clinton pays lip-service to reversing Citizens United and 
so forth, but it's easy to see from her record how disingenuous she's 
being. Trump has no earthly intention of seriously doing anything about 
campaign finance corruption, and is simply interested in using it as a 
political tool to burn down his opponents (which, don't get me wrong, they 
deserve). The only candidate in the race who would actually try to do 
something about it is Bernie Sanders... the progressive.

Finally, however serious you think the downsides of a progressive 
presidency are, to imagine they'd be more catastrophic than a Trump 
presidency seems incredible. If you elect Donald Trump, you can look 
forward to a trade war with China and Mexico that could cost us up to 7 
million American jobs and trigger a global recession:

https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2016/03/25/donald-trumps-trade-war-could-kill-millions-of-u-s-jobs/

http://www.wsj.com/articles/if-trump-launched-a-trade-war-on-asia-1459270919

His tax plan would also increase the federal deficit by over 10 TRILLION 
dollars over ten years according to the Tax Foundation, a CONSERVATIVE 
think tank:

http://taxfoundation.org/article/details-and-analysis-donald-trump-s-tax-plan

Less sympathetic analysts arrive at even higher deficit numbers:

http://ctj.org/ctjreports/2016/03/donald_trumps_tax_plan_would_cost_12_trillion.php#.VyKHg-QpUjg

So in other words, a 10 trillion dollar federal deficit, likely offset by 
gargantuan (and otherwise unnecessary) cuts to discretionary spending, is 
our BEST-case scenario under Donald Trump's tax plan, and that isn't even 
taking his disastrous trade war into account.

Add to that the deportation of American citizens to keep from separating 
the families of illegals, the deliberate killing of terrorists' family 
members, the elimination of several state departments, the dangerous 
stoking of racial tensions and the legitimization of xenophobia and 
bigotry, the egging-on of violence towards protestors and the press, the 
accelerated destruction of the environment, and the deterioration of 
international relations (if you thought Bush was bad...), and I think you 
could successfully make a case for any other candidate over the course of 
this entire race, were it between them and Trump. The only person who 
scares me nearly as much is Ted Cruz.

What do you think that Hillary, Bernie, or another candidate would do that 
would be worse than the sum total of all of that calamity? I'm not trying 
to be condescending, I'm actually asking.
